The Product:

We are creating a shop store app to attract and retain customers in our online system. This will help the customers to shop for shoes by sitting at home.

 

The problem: 

Busy businessman and worker have lack of time to visit the showroom to buy footwear for themselves.

The goal: 

Design an app named Shoeit that allow users to easily order and get their delivery at home from their favorite showroom of the town.

Responsibilities:

  • Conducting interviews

  • paper and digital wireframing

  • low and high-fidelity prototyping

  • conducting usability studies

  • accounting for accessibility, and iterating on designs.

Pain Points:

Time

Working adults are too busy to spend their time visiting the showroom to buy a pair of shoes

Lack of variety

They could see lack of variety while visiting the showroom as compared to the display and variety online. Many items can be seen at once online. 

Accessibility

There was no shopping app who only sold shoe pairs and gave a variety of shoes to the customers

Starting to work building of App :

 

After making the paper wireframes, I started working on low-fidelity wireframes and prototypes to connect the primary user flow of ordering pair of shoes, so the prototype could be used in a usability study with users.

LINK


Usability study findings:

 

Round 1 Findings:

  1. Home page lacks names of options.

  2. The price of the product needs to be mentioned in the minimized display.

Round 2 Findings:

  1. Call to action button needs to be differentiated.

  2. Proper use of icons needs to done to improve user experience.

LINK

Accessibility Considerations:

 

Provided access to users who are vision impaired through adding alt text to images for screen readers.

Used icons to help make navigation easier.

Use simple navigations like instant and touch in/out instead of smart navigation to help user navigate easily.

Learnings:


Next steps:

What I learned:

While designing the Shoeit app, I learned that the first ideas for the app are only the beginning of the process. Usability studies and peer feedback influenced each iteration of the app's designs.



  1. Conduct another round of usability studies to validate whether the pain points. users experienced have been effectively addressed.

  2. Conduct more user research to determine any new areas of need.
